01:06:26.610 --> 01:06:29.551
but in terms of the skin, I'm fascinated.

01:06:29.551 --> 01:06:32.255
- Yeah, this is a very good question.

01:06:32.255 --> 01:06:37.243
We know that the loss of
body hair in our lineage,

01:06:37.243 --> 01:06:41.060
in the Homo lineage, occurred probably

01:06:41.060 --> 01:06:44.620
more than a million and a half years ago.

01:06:44.620 --> 01:06:45.870
So the ancestor

01:06:48.028 --> 01:06:51.541
of the ancestor of the Neanderthals

01:06:51.541 --> 01:06:54.124
was a mostly hairless,

01:06:54.124 --> 01:06:57.017
sweaty member of the genus Homo.

01:06:57.017 --> 01:07:00.967
So whatever kind of species
designation you want to give,

01:07:00.967 --> 01:07:03.803
Homo erectus, Homo heidelbergensis,

01:07:03.803 --> 01:07:06.470
the predecessor to Neanderthals,

01:07:07.766 --> 01:07:10.683
this was a mostly hairless hominin.

01:07:13.555 --> 01:07:17.305
We have inferred even
before genetic evidence

01:07:18.507 --> 01:07:22.674
that a hominin that would have
been living deep in the past

01:07:23.756 --> 01:07:27.636
in a middle latitude, or in, let's say,

01:07:27.636 --> 01:07:31.389
about 40 degrees north latitude in Europe,

01:07:31.389 --> 01:07:35.396
would have lost most of it's pigmentation.

01:07:35.396 --> 01:07:39.146
So we hypothesized this
in one of our papers.

01:07:40.168 --> 01:07:42.835
But then just about 10 years ago

01:07:43.899 --> 01:07:46.232
using ancient DNA techniques

01:07:47.587 --> 01:07:51.754
an excellent Spanish human
geneticist, Carles Lalueza-Fox,

01:07:53.771 --> 01:07:57.271
was able to look at the pigmentation gene,

01:07:58.210 --> 01:08:00.543
the MC1R locus specifically,

01:08:01.387 --> 01:08:05.554
of a very important group
of Neanderthals from Spain.

01:08:07.579 --> 01:08:09.767
What he was able to determine,

01:08:09.767 --> 01:08:11.536
and this was a very clever piece

01:08:11.536 --> 01:08:13.612
of genetics that was undertaken.

01:08:13.612 --> 01:08:16.789
He was able to reconstruct the activity

01:08:16.789 --> 01:08:18.938
of this particular gene.

01:08:18.938 --> 01:08:21.449
So even though it was no Neanderthal there

01:08:21.449 --> 01:08:24.557
to sort of inhabit the gene,
if you know what I mean,

01:08:24.557 --> 01:08:27.974
he was able to show that the gene product

01:08:28.845 --> 01:08:33.012
would have been light skin,
or mostly depigmented skin.

01:08:34.264 --> 01:08:37.925
So they actually used the ancient DNA

01:08:37.925 --> 01:08:42.092
to reconstruct the action of
the melanin-producing cells

01:08:43.229 --> 01:08:45.930
and reconstructed that most individuals

01:08:45.930 --> 01:08:48.642
would have been lightly pigmented

01:08:48.642 --> 01:08:51.637
and at least, they estimated,

01:08:51.637 --> 01:08:55.977
around 10 or 20% would have had red hair.

01:08:55.977 --> 01:09:00.315
You know, I think that's a bit
more of a sort of question.

01:09:00.315 --> 01:09:03.482
But there's no doubt that the strength

01:09:04.821 --> 01:09:07.321
of natural selection was great

01:09:08.599 --> 01:09:13.252
when humans were dispersing
into high latitudes.

01:09:13.252 --> 01:09:15.835
So it was either be depigmented

01:09:17.492 --> 01:09:20.810
or have a lot of vitamin D in the diet.

01:09:20.810 --> 01:09:24.677
And I would guess in the
history of various human species

01:09:24.677 --> 01:09:27.043
and in various Homo sapiens groups,

01:09:27.043 --> 01:09:30.222
we have all sorts of mixing and matching,

01:09:30.222 --> 01:09:33.627
that there's strong selection occurring

01:09:33.627 --> 01:09:36.212
and some of that is going to be met

01:09:36.212 --> 01:09:38.808
through genetic modifications

01:09:38.808 --> 01:09:42.677
of readily available genetic
variation when it's there,

01:09:42.677 --> 01:09:46.688
and other times it's going
to be met by dietary changes,

01:09:46.688 --> 01:09:49.935
and other times it's not
going to be met at all

01:09:49.935 --> 01:09:52.852
and the populations become extinct.

01:09:56.962 --> 01:09:58.239
- [Woman] I'm going to
ask you a silly question,

01:09:58.239 --> 01:09:59.201
if that's all right.

01:09:59.201 --> 01:10:00.468
- Go ahead.

01:10:00.468 --> 01:10:02.962
- [Woman] So if you have
a black-and-white cat

01:10:02.962 --> 01:10:07.129
and you shave it, its skin is
also black-and-white patchy,

01:10:08.598 --> 01:10:11.384
so why, I mean, obviously
that's a carnivore,

01:10:11.384 --> 01:10:14.462
but why is it that human
skin and pelage coloration

01:10:14.462 --> 01:10:17.326
is so uniform on an individual?

01:10:17.326 --> 01:10:19.591
- Yeah, it's a great question,

01:10:19.591 --> 01:10:22.288
and it's not a silly question at all.

01:10:22.288 --> 01:10:25.352
We see throughout primates,

01:10:25.352 --> 01:10:27.935
and especially throughout apes,

01:10:29.965 --> 01:10:32.048
that we lose our pattern.

01:10:32.916 --> 01:10:34.988
So there are some monkeys

01:10:34.988 --> 01:10:38.541
that have beautifully patterned coats

01:10:38.541 --> 01:10:42.651
and that have similarly
patterned skin under the coats.

01:10:42.651 --> 01:10:46.162
But as soon as we get into the ape lineage

01:10:46.162 --> 01:10:50.647
we lose, and especially the
large, the African ape lineage,

01:10:50.647 --> 01:10:53.044
we lose all of that patterning

01:10:53.044 --> 01:10:56.427
for genetic reasons that
we still don't understand.

01:10:56.427 --> 01:10:58.457
So when you shave an orangutan,

01:10:58.457 --> 01:11:01.982
you shave a gorilla or a chimpanzee,

01:11:01.982 --> 01:11:05.372
it's all the same color underneath.

01:11:05.372 --> 01:11:08.987
This is a real question as to why,

01:11:08.987 --> 01:11:12.519
why we lose this, the relationship

01:11:12.519 --> 01:11:16.728
between the hair color and
the underlying skin color.

01:11:16.728 --> 01:11:20.014
And this is, as I say,
it is an open question

01:11:20.014 --> 01:11:23.666
that primate biologists
who are studying skin

01:11:23.666 --> 01:11:27.532
and hair coloration have yet to answer.

01:11:27.532 --> 01:11:30.699
But a very good one, not silly at all.

01:11:31.758 --> 01:11:34.212
- [Woman] Hi, I have two quick questions

01:11:34.212 --> 01:11:36.453
The first one is will you be covering

01:11:36.453 --> 01:11:39.094
in the following lectures
what some refer to

01:11:39.094 --> 01:11:42.208
as the epidemic of vitamin D deficiencies?

01:11:42.208 --> 01:11:43.905
And my second question is

01:11:43.905 --> 01:11:47.140
how has skin pigmentation
evolved independently

01:11:47.140 --> 01:11:49.648
from other phenotypes if
melanin is responsible

01:11:49.648 --> 01:11:51.477
for the color of not only skin

01:11:51.477 --> 01:11:53.229
but our eyes and our hair color?

01:11:53.229 --> 01:11:56.440
- The first question is easy, yes,

01:11:56.440 --> 01:12:00.457
I will be talking at length
about vitamin D deficiency.

01:12:00.457 --> 01:12:04.447
What's interesting about
the melanin systems

01:12:04.447 --> 01:12:06.751
in, you know, in the hair and eyes

01:12:06.751 --> 01:12:10.918
is that they are not under
as strong natural selection.

01:12:13.414 --> 01:12:16.313
It's important to have hair on the head.

01:12:16.313 --> 01:12:19.008
We know that the hair
on the head, scalp hair,

01:12:19.008 --> 01:12:23.228
does serve an important
thermoregulatory function

01:12:23.228 --> 01:12:25.640
on the surface of the head,

01:12:25.640 --> 01:12:29.444
but the color of the
hair probably hasn't been

01:12:29.444 --> 01:12:31.874
under strong natural selection.

01:12:31.874 --> 01:12:35.134
But, and we know also that
it seems to be controlled

01:12:35.134 --> 01:12:38.717
by many fewer genes
than skin pigmentation.

01:12:39.573 --> 01:12:42.560
To make a long and interesting story short

01:12:42.560 --> 01:12:45.555
what has happened in the
history of human dispersals

01:12:45.555 --> 01:12:48.778
is that there hasn't
been so much selection

01:12:48.778 --> 01:12:52.514
of hair color and texture or eye color

01:12:52.514 --> 01:12:55.764
but, rather, loss of genetic variation.

01:12:57.752 --> 01:13:02.357
So that when you have a
limited palette of genes

01:13:02.357 --> 01:13:05.129
and you lose some of that variation

01:13:05.129 --> 01:13:08.796
because the dispersing
populations are small

01:13:10.184 --> 01:13:13.934
then you're sort of
stuck with all dark eyes.

01:13:15.327 --> 01:13:19.205
If you look at eastern Asian populations

01:13:19.205 --> 01:13:23.893
all individuals have darkly
pigmented hair and eyes

01:13:23.893 --> 01:13:25.984
and I would venture that
that's not a product

01:13:25.984 --> 01:13:29.306
of natural selection, it was an accident

01:13:29.306 --> 01:13:33.522
of small-population effect
in human dispersals.

01:13:33.522 --> 01:13:36.189
Similarly in northwestern Europe

01:13:37.325 --> 01:13:41.099
where we know we have strong
population bottlenecks

01:13:41.099 --> 01:13:45.355
occurring in the late
Pleistocene and early Holocene

01:13:45.355 --> 01:13:48.464
that we have repeated genetic bottlenecks

01:13:48.464 --> 01:13:50.071
and loss of variation.

01:13:50.071 --> 01:13:53.974
So we might get some really
interesting variations

01:13:53.974 --> 01:13:57.807
being thrown up in hair
color and in eye color

01:13:58.688 --> 01:14:03.106
but this isn't, it
hasn't been selected for.

01:14:03.106 --> 01:14:07.207
Initially it is there because
of a small-population effect,

01:14:07.207 --> 01:14:09.790
I would venture, and then later

01:14:10.866 --> 01:14:15.033
it may become acted upon by
natural or by social selection.

01:14:16.721 --> 01:14:20.888
We do have evidence for
social and sexual selection

01:14:22.675 --> 01:14:27.040
of certain of these traits
in certain populations.

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:29.912
But I think it's really
important that we look carefully

01:14:29.912 --> 01:14:33.745
at the range of genetic
and population factors

01:14:34.870 --> 01:14:38.640
that are occurring and the
sequence in which they acted,

01:14:38.640 --> 01:14:40.905
and that we don't just say, oh, yes, yeah,

01:14:40.905 --> 01:14:43.868
blondes evolved under sexual selection.

01:14:43.868 --> 01:14:45.220
No.

01:14:45.220 --> 01:14:49.449
It was a genetic accident
probably then followed

01:14:49.449 --> 01:14:53.126
by some social and sexual selection.

01:14:53.126 --> 01:14:53.959
- [Woman] Thank you.

01:14:53.959 --> 01:14:54.792
- Mm-hmm.

01:14:58.008 --> 01:14:59.682
- [Man] Two sort of questions.

01:14:59.682 --> 01:15:03.765
One, why is hair regionally
retained on the body?

01:15:04.838 --> 01:15:07.332
And a related question, not for myself,

01:15:07.332 --> 01:15:09.530
but for those in the
audience who might care,

01:15:09.530 --> 01:15:11.657
is there a selective
advantage or disadvantage

01:15:11.657 --> 01:15:13.327
to male pattern baldness?

01:15:13.327 --> 01:15:17.160
- (laughs) A common question.

01:15:18.281 --> 01:15:22.020
Usually put to me by people
with less scalp hair.

01:15:22.020 --> 01:15:23.998
In answer to your first question,

01:15:23.998 --> 01:15:27.270
this is a really good question.

01:15:27.270 --> 01:15:30.056
Answers to why did we retain

01:15:30.056 --> 01:15:32.866
these regional accumulations of hair

01:15:32.866 --> 01:15:36.556
and in addition to pubic
hair, and axillary hair,

01:15:36.556 --> 01:15:40.667
and scalp hair, why do
men have facial hair?

01:15:40.667 --> 01:15:43.746
The jury is still out, to be generous,

01:15:43.746 --> 01:15:44.900
on most of these things.

01:15:44.900 --> 01:15:47.522
I think scalp hair we
can make a strong case

01:15:47.522 --> 01:15:51.817
for the fact that it does
locally protect the scalp

01:15:51.817 --> 01:15:55.136
from solar radiation and overheating,

01:15:55.136 --> 01:15:57.460
and that is allows sort of a,

01:15:57.460 --> 01:16:02.360
a space in which the skin
can sweat and lose heat.

01:16:02.360 --> 01:16:04.153
So I think that's important.

01:16:04.153 --> 01:16:06.640
With pubic and axillary hair,

01:16:06.640 --> 01:16:10.807
I think the primary function
is dispersal of pheromones,

01:16:11.850 --> 01:16:16.017
because the apocrine glands
that are concentrated there

01:16:17.109 --> 01:16:19.987
secrete important molecules

01:16:19.987 --> 01:16:22.786
that are used in chemical communication.

01:16:22.786 --> 01:16:26.504
We do our level best
to silence them, right,

01:16:26.504 --> 01:16:29.683
in modern societies, and
we consider it antisocial

01:16:29.683 --> 01:16:32.175
when we can smell somebody,

01:16:32.175 --> 01:16:36.342
but smell is part of our
armamentarium of communication

01:16:37.557 --> 01:16:39.150
and this has been very important.

01:16:39.150 --> 01:16:43.728
We know that it still is
important in sexual attractiveness

01:16:43.728 --> 01:16:48.122
even though we do our very
best to eliminate smells.

01:16:48.122 --> 01:16:52.289
So I think this is a fascinating
and still ill-studied area.

01:16:53.976 --> 01:16:56.421
With beard hair there has been a lot

01:16:56.421 --> 01:17:00.588
of interesting recent work
on beards as sexual signals,

01:17:02.606 --> 01:17:06.023
as signals of male maturity and male age.

01:17:07.867 --> 01:17:12.597
Because the beard changes
color generally more rapidly

01:17:12.597 --> 01:17:15.104
than other parts of body hair.

01:17:15.104 --> 01:17:18.252
And so not only does the
fullness of the male beard

01:17:18.252 --> 01:17:21.252
indicate sort of a fully mature male

01:17:23.659 --> 01:17:27.066
but also the change of
color can be a very accurate

01:17:27.066 --> 01:17:30.146
chronological indicator of male age,

01:17:30.146 --> 01:17:33.896
and that may have been
important in the past.

01:17:35.169 --> 01:17:39.252
So these are interesting
hypotheses, all of them,

01:17:40.247 --> 01:17:42.871
that have not been tested very well.

01:17:42.871 --> 01:17:47.038
There is still a huge amount
of work to be done on hair.

01:17:48.297 --> 01:17:51.511
- [Woman] Your very
interesting hairy timeline

01:17:51.511 --> 01:17:55.753
at the beginning showed
a rather rapid loss

01:17:55.753 --> 01:17:57.773
of hair in the middle.

01:17:57.773 --> 01:18:02.334
Is it real, and if so, what
do you think caused it?

01:18:02.334 --> 01:18:05.658
- Yes, well, that, the rapid loss of hair

01:18:05.658 --> 01:18:08.395
was probably fairly rapid.

01:18:08.395 --> 01:18:12.087
For this we really need to
look to the paleontologists

01:18:12.087 --> 01:18:13.585
and look at the transition

01:18:13.585 --> 01:18:16.335
from sort of an Australopithecine

01:18:17.778 --> 01:18:19.945
to a modern Homo skeleton.

01:18:21.568 --> 01:18:23.950
That occurred over the course

01:18:23.950 --> 01:18:26.700
of probably a half million years.

01:18:27.990 --> 01:18:32.030
So, you know, I can't
really say how quickly

01:18:32.030 --> 01:18:34.897
the change in skin would've occurred,

01:18:34.897 --> 01:18:38.314
but certainly going along with a skeleton

01:18:39.162 --> 01:18:42.830
that is fit for walking and running

01:18:42.830 --> 01:18:45.012
we know that there
would have been build-up

01:18:45.012 --> 01:18:48.795
of excess body heat under
hot environmental conditions,

01:18:48.795 --> 01:18:51.064
and if the only physiological mechanisms

01:18:51.064 --> 01:18:54.978
available to you are from
the surface of the body

01:18:54.978 --> 01:18:57.715
through radiant and evaporative heat loss

01:18:57.715 --> 01:19:00.697
there would've been
strong natural selection

01:19:00.697 --> 01:19:04.609
for complete loss of functional body hair.

01:19:04.609 --> 01:19:08.496
And so I would guess that
transition was quite rapid,

01:19:08.496 --> 01:19:10.774
and that little sort of signaling

01:19:10.774 --> 01:19:13.937
and evolutionary developmental biology

01:19:13.937 --> 01:19:17.571
toward increased differentiation
of eccrine sweat glands,

01:19:17.571 --> 01:19:21.790
I think the switch was thrown and probably

01:19:21.790 --> 01:19:25.040
the genetic architecture of that change

01:19:25.972 --> 01:19:28.972
was under strong positive selection.

01:19:31.029 --> 01:19:32.945
- [Woman] I have a very young niece,

01:19:32.945 --> 01:19:35.555
who just had kidney transplant.

01:19:35.555 --> 01:19:37.805
She's of Scottish heritage.

01:19:39.557 --> 01:19:42.284
They've said people who've
had kidney transplants,

01:19:42.284 --> 01:19:44.113
of course they're taking
immune suppressants

01:19:44.113 --> 01:19:46.739
and the doctors are really dismayed

01:19:46.739 --> 01:19:50.685
that oftentimes they'll get
skin cancer within five years.

01:19:50.685 --> 01:19:52.356
So I was just wondering,

01:19:52.356 --> 01:19:55.606
shouldn't they all be taking vitamin D?

01:19:56.943 --> 01:19:59.231
- This is a really good question

01:19:59.231 --> 01:20:00.648
and I talk a lot

01:20:02.176 --> 01:20:06.651
to nephrologists and
kidney transplant surgeons

01:20:06.651 --> 01:20:08.264
all around the world about this

01:20:08.264 --> 01:20:11.681
because it is one of the major challenges

01:20:14.592 --> 01:20:17.503
to keep people healthy
with respect to vitamin D.

01:20:17.503 --> 01:20:22.303
In the case of your relative
with lightly pigmented skin

01:20:22.303 --> 01:20:26.866
it is really important that
she stay out of the sun.

01:20:26.866 --> 01:20:29.457
So I would say that she needs to talk

01:20:29.457 --> 01:20:32.874
to her physicians quickly and efficiently

01:20:34.257 --> 01:20:38.304
about what program of
vitamin D supplementation

01:20:38.304 --> 01:20:40.726
she should take to stay healthy

01:20:40.726 --> 01:20:45.374
because the majority of,
or, I should say many,

01:20:45.374 --> 01:20:48.520
if not the majority of
kidney transplant patients

01:20:48.520 --> 01:20:51.020
are badly vitamin D deficient.

01:20:53.182 --> 01:20:54.806
- [Woman] And what about folate,

01:20:54.806 --> 01:20:56.338
or is that a totally different issue?

01:20:56.338 --> 01:20:57.737
- Folate is a completely different story

01:20:57.737 --> 01:20:59.436
and folate is, you know,

01:20:59.436 --> 01:21:01.819
you can get it really, really easily.

01:21:01.819 --> 01:21:04.764
There are no easy dietary
sources of vitamin D

01:21:04.764 --> 01:21:08.324
unless you really seek out mackerel

01:21:08.324 --> 01:21:11.491
and other specific kinds of oily fish.

01:21:12.869 --> 01:21:16.173
But folate you can get from
green leafy vegetables,

01:21:16.173 --> 01:21:19.738
mostly of any kind, citrus
fruits, whole grains.

01:21:19.738 --> 01:21:22.164
You can get folate from
a variety of sources,

01:21:22.164 --> 01:21:24.029
so it's easy to top up on folate.

01:21:24.029 --> 01:21:26.477
Less easy to top up on vitamin D.

01:21:26.477 --> 01:21:27.812
- [Woman] So, then, supplements.

01:21:27.812 --> 01:21:31.535
- Yes a supplement but
talk to the physicians

01:21:31.535 --> 01:21:34.117
to determine the dosage.

01:21:34.117 --> 01:21:36.291
- Okay, well, let's thank
our speaker once again,

01:21:36.291 --> 01:21:37.753
and thanks very much for coming.

01:21:37.753 --> 01:21:39.544
- Thank you, thanks very much.

01:21:39.544 --> 01:21:42.211
(upbeat music)

